A prime p satisfying the congruence {{math|(p&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1)! ≡&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1&nbsp;+&nbsp;''Bp''&nbsp;mod&nbsp;''p''<sup>2</sup>}} with small {{math|{{abs|''B''}}}} can be called a '''near-Wilson prime'''. Near-Wilson primes with {{math|1=''B''&nbsp;=&nbsp;0}} represent Wilson primes. The following table lists all such primes with {{math|{{abs|''B''}}&nbsp;≤&nbsp;100}} from {{10^|6}} up to 4{{e|11}}:<ref name="Search"/>
===Wilson numbers=== A '''Wilson number''' is a natural number ''n'' such that ''W''(''n'') ≡ 0 (mod ''n''<sup>2</sup>), where <math>W(n) = \prod_\stackrel{1 \le k \le n}{\gcd(k,n)=1}{k}+e</math>, the constant ''e'' = 1 [[if and only if]] ''n'' have a [[primitive root modulo n|primitive root]], otherwise, ''e'' = -1<ref>see [[Wilson's theorem#Gauss.27s generalization|Gauss's generalization of Wilson's theorem]]</ref> For every natural number ''n'', ''W''(''n'') is divisible by ''n'', and the quotients (called generalized [[Wilson quotient]]s) are listed in {{oeis|id=A157249}}. The Wilson numbers are :1, 5, 13, 563, 5971, 558771, 1964215, 8121909, 12326713, 23025711, 26921605, 341569806, 399292158, ... {{OEIS|id=A157250}}
If a Wilson number ''n'' is prime, then ''n'' is a Wilson prime. There are 13 Wilson numbers up to 5{{e|8}}.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1090/S0025-5718-98-00951-X | first1 = Takashi | last1 = Agoh | first2 = Karl | last2 = Dilcher | first3 = Ladislav | last3 = Skula | authorlink3 = Ladislav Skula| title=Wilson quotients for composite moduli | journal=Math. Comput. | volume=67 | issue=222 | pages=843–861 | year=1998 | url=http://www.ams.org/journals/mcom/1998-67-222/S0025-5718-98-00951-X/S0025-5718-98-00951-X.pdf}}</ref>
